t is unknown how many party members ran in the 1993 and 1997 elections as independents.\n\n== Provincial sections ==\nThe Communist Party of Canada has provincial wings which contest general elections at the provincial level. In most provinces the provincial wing's name is in the format \"Communist Party of Canada ([Province])\". These include:\n* {{flag|Alberta}}: [[Communist Party \u2013 Alberta]]\n* {{flag|British Columbia}}: [[Communist Party of British Columbia]]\n* {{flag|Manitoba}}: [[Communist Party of Canada (Manitoba)]]\n* {{flag|Ontario}}: [[Communist Party of Canada (Ontario)]]\n* {{flag|Quebec}}: [[Communist Party of Quebec]]\n* {{flag|Saskatchewan}}: [[Communist Party of Canada (Saskatchewan)]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada|Politics|Communism}}\n* [[:Category:Canadian communists]]\n* [[Communist Party candidates, 2000 Canadian federal election]] <!-- Note: Communist Party of Canada (Marxist\u2013Leninist) is a different party. -->\n* [[Communist Party candidates, 2004 Canadian federal election]]\n* [[Communist Party candidates, 2006 Canadian federal election]]\n* [[Communist Party candidates, 2008 Canadian federal election]]\n* [[Communist Party candidates, 2011 Canadian federal election]]\n*[[Communist Party of Canada candidates in the 2015 Canadian federal election]]\n*[[Communist Party of Canada candidates in the 2019 Canadian federal election]]\n* [[Organization for Jewish Colonization in Russia]]\n* [[PROFUNC]]\n* [[Rebel Youth]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Communist Party of Canada}}\n* {{Official website|http://communist-party.ca/}}\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/CanadasPartySocialism Canada's Party of Socialism: History of the Communist Party of Canada 1921-1976]'' - official account of the party's history\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/227/*/http://communist-party.ca/ Communist Party of Canada - Canadian Political Parties and Political Interest Groups] - Web Archive created by the University of Toronto Libraries\n* [http://atom.archives.sfu.ca/index.php/communist-party-of-canada-fonds Records of the Communist Party of Canada are held by Simon Fraser University's Special Collections and Rare Books]\n* [https://discoverarchives.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/robert-s-kenny-papers Communist Party of Canada manuscript and printed materials collection] - Robert S. Kenny Papers at Thomas Fisher Rare Book Library\n{{Canadian federal political parties}}\n{{XV International Brigade}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Communist Party Of Canada}}\n[[Category:Communist Party of Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Canada]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Canada]]\n[[Category:Communism in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communist_Party_of_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Gordon Clubb", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian former rower|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Gordon Clubb\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Australian\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|5|22|df=yes}}\n| children       = Amelia Clubb, Will Clubb\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| education = [[Sydney Grammar School]]\n| headercolor = skyblue\n| club = [[Sydney Rowing Club]]\n| nationals = [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] 1977\u20131980 <br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1977\u201380 M4+]]<br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1978 M2-]]<br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1979 M4X]]\n|olympics = \n}}\n\n'''Gordon Clubb''' (born 22 May 1953) is an Australian former [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He was an eight-time national champion rower who represented at three world championships. He won four consecutive Australian national championship titles in a coxed four from 1977 to 1980.\n\n==Rowing family==\nBorn in [[Dubbo, New South Wales]], <ref>[https://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/sportingwalloffame/sportsperson088.html Mosman Sporting Hall of Fame]</ref> Clubb attended [[Sydney Grammar School]] where he was took up rowing and matriculated in 1971. His father Gordon Clubb Snr was a [[Sydney Rowing Club]] member from 1934 and a committee man from 1946. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/09-1.php SRC 1940s history]</ref> Gordon Clubb Snr had rowed for Australia as a single sculler in a 1940 Trans Tasman series against New Zealand <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/trans-tasman-series/1888-1965.html Trans Tasman series history]</ref> and coached his sons at Sydney Rowing Club in the 1970s. Gordon's younger brother [[Ian Clubb]] rowed in champion [[Sydney Rowing Club|SRC]] and New South Wales [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] crews of the late 1970s and rowed for Australia from 1976 to 1979.\n\n==Club and state rowing==\nGordon Clubb first made state selection for New South Wales in 1977 in the six seat of the men's eight which contested and won the [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] at the Interstate Regatta within the [[Australian Rowing Championships]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1977.php#M8 |title=1977 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723122820/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1977.php#M8 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He rowed in another King's Cup winning New South Wales crews in 1978. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1978.php#M8 |title=1978 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410071849/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1978.php#M8 |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was a reserve for the New South Wales eight in 1979 and stroked the 1980 crew to second place.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1980.php#M8 |title=1980 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706191240/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1980.php#M8 |archive-date=6 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the 1974 [[Australian Rowing Championships|Australian Championships]] Clubb contested the double  scull national title with [[Kim Mackney]] and placed fourth in that event. He also rowed to second place in a composite coxless four.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1974.html#m2 1974 Austn C'ships]</ref> The following year in 1975 he contested both  the coxed and coxless four titles in [[Sydney Rowing Club|Sydney]] colours placing second and third.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1975.html#m2x 1975 Austn C'ships]</ref>\n\nAt the 1976 [[Australian Rowing Championships|Australian Championships]] Clubb contested the quad scull national title in a composite [[Sydney Rowing Club |Sydney]]/[[UTS Haberfield Rowing Club|Haberfield]] crew and placed second in that event.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1975.html#m2 1976 Austn C'ships]</ref> In 1977 he rowed to second place with [[UTS Haberfield Rowing Club|Haberfield]]'s Dick Reddel in an attempt at the coxless pair national title and that same year with his brother and [[Islay Lee]] in a Sydney coxed four he rowed to a national championship win. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1977.html#m2x 1977 Austn C'ships]</ref>He then successfully defended that same title in 1978, 1979 <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1979.html#mcoxed4 1979 Austn C'ships]</ref> and 1980 each time in the two seat. In 1978 paired with his brother he also won the national title in a coxless pair.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1978.html#m2x 1978 Austn C'ships]</ref> In 1979 he also rowed in an all-Sydney quad to take the quad sculls title. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1979.html#m2x 1979 Austn C'ships]</ref>\n\n==International representative rowing==\nClubb made his Australian representative debut in the six seat of the Australian men's eight selected for the [[1977 World Rowing Championships]] in Amsterdam. Six of the crew including his brother Ian were from the [[Sydney Rowing Club]]'s senior eight. They missed the A final and rowed to overall tenth place.<ref name=\"Career\">[http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/38579/clubb-gordon Clubb at World Rowing]</ref> \n<ref name=\"Career\" />\n\nFor the [[1978 World Rowing Championships]] in Lake Karapiro, the successful New South Wales King's Cup eight was again selected and was composed of all Sydney men excepting [[Gary Uebergang]] and [[Athol MacDonald]] from Mosman.<ref name=\"Career\" /> With Clubb seated at six, the Australian eight placed second in their heat, third in the repechage and in the final finished fourth being edged out for third by the host nation New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1978-LakeKarapiro.html |title=1978 World C'ships |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910140539/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1978-LakeKarapiro.html |archive-date=10 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1979 World Rowing Championships]] in Lake Karapiro, sitting in front of his brother Clubb stroked the Australian coxless four which was eliminated in the repechage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1979-Bled.html |title=1979 World C'ships |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511034940/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1979-Bled.html |archive-date=11 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was his final Australian representative appearance of both Clubb brothers.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FISA|38579}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clubb, Gordon}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male rowers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian former rower|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Gordon Clubb\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Australian\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1953|5|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| education = [[Sydney Grammar School]]\n| headercolor = skyblue\n| club = [[Sydney Rowing Club]]\n| nationals = [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] 1977\u20131980 <br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1977\u201380 M4+]]<br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1978 M2-]]<br> [[Australian Rowing Championships|Aust Champion 1979 M4X]]\n|olympics = \n}}\n\n'''Gordon Clubb''' (born 22 May 1953) is an Australian former [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He was an eight-time national champion rower who represented at three world championships. He won four consecutive Australian national championship titles in a coxed four from 1977 to 1980.\n\n==Rowing family==\nBorn in [[Dubbo, New South Wales]], <ref>[https://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/sportingwalloffame/sportsperson088.html Mosman Sporting Hall of Fame]</ref> Clubb attended [[Sydney Grammar School]] where he was took up rowing and matriculated in 1971. His father Gordon Clubb Snr was a [[Sydney Rowing Club]] member from 1934 and a committee man from 1946. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/09-1.php SRC 1940s history]</ref> Gordon Clubb Snr had rowed for Australia as a single sculler in a 1940 Trans Tasman series against New Zealand <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/trans-tasman-series/1888-1965.html Trans Tasman series history]</ref> and coached his sons at Sydney Rowing Club in the 1970s. Gordon's younger brother [[Ian Clubb]] rowed in champion [[Sydney Rowing Club|SRC]] and New South Wales [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] crews of the late 1970s and rowed for Australia from 1976 to 1979.\n\n==Club and state rowing==\nGordon Clubb first made state selection for New South Wales in 1977 in the six seat of the men's eight which contested and won the [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] at the Interstate Regatta within the [[Australian Rowing Championships]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1977.php#M8 |title=1977 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723122820/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1977.php#M8 |archive-date=23 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He rowed in another King's Cup winning New South Wales crews in 1978. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1978.php#M8 |title=1978 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410071849/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1978.php#M8 |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was a reserve for the New South Wales eight in 1979 and stroked the 1980 crew to second place.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1980.php#M8 |title=1980 Interstate Regatta |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706191240/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1980.php#M8 |archive-date=6 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the 1974 [[Australian Rowing Championships|Australian Championships]] Clubb contested the double  scull national title with [[Kim Mackney]] and placed fourth in that event. He also rowed to second place in a composite coxless four.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1974.html#m2 1974 Austn C'ships]</ref> The following year in 1975 he contested both  the coxed and coxless four titles in [[Sydney Rowing Club|Sydney]] colours placing second and third.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1975.html#m2x 1975 Austn C'ships]</ref>\n\nAt the 1976 [[Australian Rowing Championships|Australian Championships]] Clubb contested the quad scull national title in a composite [[Sydney Rowing Club |Sydney]]/[[UTS Haberfield Rowing Club|Haberfield]] crew and placed second in that event.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1975.html#m2 1976 Austn C'ships]</ref> In 1977 he rowed to second place with [[UTS Haberfield Rowing Club|Haberfield]]'s Dick Reddel in an attempt at the coxless pair national title and that same year with his brother and [[Islay Lee]] in a Sydney coxed four he rowed to a national championship win. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1977.html#m2x 1977 Austn C'ships]</ref>He then successfully defended that same title in 1978, 1979 <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1979.html#mcoxed4 1979 Austn C'ships]</ref> and 1980 each time in the two seat. In 1978 paired with his brother he also won the national title in a coxless pair.<ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1978.html#m2x 1978 Austn C'ships]</ref> In 1979 he also rowed in an all-Sydney quad to take the quad sculls title. <ref>[http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/national-championships/1979.html#m2x 1979 Austn C'ships]</ref>\n\n==International representative rowing==\nClubb made his Australian representative debut in the six seat of the Australian men's eight selected for the [[1977 World Rowing Championships]] in Amsterdam. Six of the crew including his brother Ian were from the [[Sydney Rowing Club]]'s senior eight. They missed the A final and rowed to overall tenth place.<ref name=\"Career\">[http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/38579/clubb-gordon Clubb at World Rowing]</ref> \n<ref name=\"Career\" />\n\nFor the [[1978 World Rowing Championships]] in Lake Karapiro, the successful New South Wales King's Cup eight was again selected and was composed of all Sydney men excepting [[Gary Uebergang]] and [[Athol MacDonald]] from Mosman.<ref name=\"Career\" /> With Clubb seated at six, the Australian eight placed second in their heat, third in the repechage and in the final finished fourth being edged out for third by the host nation New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1978-LakeKarapiro.html |title=1978 World C'ships |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910140539/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1978-LakeKarapiro.html |archive-date=10 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1979 World Rowing Championships]] in Lake Karapiro, sitting in front of his brother Clubb stroked the Australian coxless four which was eliminated in the repechage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1979-Bled.html |title=1979 World C'ships |access-date=13 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511034940/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/world-championships/1979-Bled.html |archive-date=11 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was his final Australian representative appearance of both Clubb brothers.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FISA|38579}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clubb, Gordon}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male rowers]]\n", "name_user": "Acwlg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Clubb"}
{"title_page": "Felice Napoleone Canevaro", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   =\n | name               = Felice Napoleone Canevaro\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   =\n | image              = File:Felice Napoleone Canevaro.jpg\n | image_size         = 250px\n | image_upright      =\n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = Felice Napoleone Canevaro\n | caption            = Felice Napoleone Canevaro in 1898\n | order              =\n | office             = [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n | term_start         = 29 June 1898\n | term_end           = 14 May 1899\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            = [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n | president          =\n | governor_general   =\n | primeminister      = [[Luigi Pelloux]]\n | taoiseach          =\n | chancellor         =\n | governor           =\n | vicepresident      =\n | viceprimeminister  =\n | deputy             =\n | lieutenant         =\n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup =\n | constituency       =\n | majority           =\n | predecessor        = [[Raffaele Cappelli]]\n | successor          = [[Emilio Visconti Venosta]]\n | prior_term         =\n | order2             =\n | office2            =  [[Italian Minister of the Navy]]\n | term_start2        =  1 June 1898\n | term_end2          =  29 June 1898\n | alongside2         =\n | monarch2           =  [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n | president2         =\n | governor_general2  =\n | primeminister2     =  [[Antonio di Rudini]]\n | chancellor2        =\n | taoiseach2         =\n | governor2          =\n | vicepresident2     =\n | viceprimeminister2 =\n | deputy2            =\n | lieutenant2        =\n | succeeding2        =\n | predecessor2       =  [[Alessandro Assinari di San Marzano]]\n | successor2         =  Giuseppe Palumbo\n | parliamentarygroup2=\n | constituency2      =\n | majority2          =\n | prior_term2        =\n| order3             =\n | office3            =  [[Senator of the Kingdom of Italy]]\n | term_start3        =\n | term_end3          =\n | alongside3         =\n | monarch3           =  [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n[[:it:XIX legislatura del Regno d'Italia|XIX Legislature]]\n | data3              =\n | legislature3       =\n | president3         =\n | governor_general3  =\n | primeminister3     =\n | chancellor3        =\n | taoiseach3         =\n | governor3          =\n | vicepresident3     =\n | viceprimeminister3 =\n | deputy3            =\n | lieutenant3        =\n | succeeding3        =\n | predecessor3       =\n | successor3         =\n | parliamentarygroup3=\n | constituency3      =\n | majority3          =\n | prior_term3        =\n}}\n\n'''Felice Napoleone Canevaro''' (7 July 1838 \u2013 30 December 1926) was an Italian admiral and politician and a [[Senate of the Kingdom of Italy|senator of the Kingdom of Italy]]. He served as both Minister of the Navy and [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] and was a recipient of the [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]. In his naval career, he was best known for his actions during the [[Italian Wars of Independence]] and later as commander of the [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] off [[Crete]] in 1897\u20131898.\n\n==Biography==\nThe descendant of a [[Liguria]]n family originally from [[Zoagli]], Canevaro was born in [[Lima]], [[Peru]], to Giuseppe and Francesca Velaga.<ref name=treccani>{{cite web |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/felice-napoleone-canevaro_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ |first=Gabriele  |last=Mariano |title=Canevaro, Felice Napoleone |work=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani  |volume=18 |year=1975 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===Naval career===\nIn 1852, Canevaro was admitted to the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]]'s Royal Navy School at [[Genoa]], completing the course of instruction in 1855 and receiving a [[Commissioned officer|commission]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign second class]].\n\n====Italian Wars of Independence====\nIn 1859, with the rank of second [[Lieutenant (naval)|lieutenant]], Canevaro took part in [[Royal Sardinian Navy]] operations in the [[Adriatic Sea]] aboard the [[Troop transport|transport]] ''Beroldo'' and the sailing [[frigate]] {{ship|Italian frigate|Des Geneys||2}} during the [[Second Italian War of Independence]].<ref name=treccani/>\n\nIn 1860, Canevaro arrived in [[Palermo]], [[Sicily]], aboard {{ship|Italian frigate|Maria Adelaide||2}}, the [[flagship]] of the Sardinian [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]]. When the supporters of the Italian nationalist leader [[General officer|General]] [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] organized their navy, he resigned from the Royal Sardinian Navy to enlist in the Garibaldian navy. Aboard the [[steam frigate]] ''Tukory'' on the night of 13 August 1860, Canevaro distinguished himself during an unsuccessful attempt to board the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]] steam [[ship-of-the-line]] ''Monarca'' while she was anchored in the port of [[Castellammare di Stabia]]. He received the [[Silver Medal of Military Valor]] for his actions during this engagement.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nIn the autumn of 1860, Canevarro was reinstated in the Royal Sardinian Navy. While embarked on the Sardinian steam frigate {{ship|Italian frigate|Carlo Alberto|1853|2}} from December 1860 to March 1861, he took part in the [[Siege of Gaeta (1860)|Siege of Gaeta]] and a [[siege]] of [[Messina]] during operations in which ''Carlo Alberto'' repeatedly exchanged fire with hostile forces at close range along the coast. After the campaign, he was made a Knight of the [[Military Order of Savoy]], and in 1863, he was promoted to ''[[Lieutenant (naval)|luogotenente de vascello]]''. In 1865\u20131866, Canevaro was on board the steam frigate {{ship|Italian frigate|Principe Umberto||2}}, under the command [[Guglielmo Acton]], during a long cruise that included a [[transatlantic voyage]], operations along the [[Atlantic]] coast of [[South America]], a transit of the [[Strait of Magellan]] into the [[Pacific Ocean]], and steaming up the coast of [[Chile]].<ref name=treccani/>\n[[File:Italian battleship Italia officers and guns.jpg|300px|thumb|left|Canevaro and the [[Commissioned officer|officers]] of the [[battleship]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}} pose under a pair of her {{convert|17|in|mm|adj=on|0}} guns.]]\nOn returning to Italy, he was assigned to the [[broadside ironclad]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re di Portogallo||2}}, commanded by Augusto Riboty. Aboard ''Re di Portogallo'', he took part in 1866 in the [[Third Italian War of Independence]], during which the ship was engaged in operations against the fortress of [[Vis (island)|Lissa]] in the [[Adriatic Sea]]. As [[flagship]] of the 3rd Division, and with Canevaro aboard as the division's chief-of-staff, ''Re di Portogallo'' led the division's attack on [[Porto San Giorgio]] on 18 July 1866.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n[[File:The Admirals of the Powers in Cretan Waters.JPG|300px|left|thumb|\"The Admirals of the Powers in Cretan Waters\" (Sketch from ''[[Black and White (magazine)|Black and White]]'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1897). Canevaro, serving at the time as commander of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]], is fourth from left.]]\n[[File:Bombardment of Canea 21 February 1897.JPG|300px|thumb|left|Illustration as it appeared in ''[[The Graphic]]'' on 13 March 1897 of warships of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] bombarding Christian insurgents above [[Chania]], [[Crete]], on 21 February 1897. It probably is reversed.]]\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  =\n| name              = Felice Napoleono Canevaro\n| honorific_suffix  =\n| image         =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| native_name       =\n| native_name_lang  =\n| birth_name    =\n| other_name    =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1838|07|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lima]], [[Peru]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1926|12|30|1838|07|07|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Venice]], [[Italy]]\n| placeofburial_label =\n| placeofburial =\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = *[[Kingdom of Sardinia]]\n* [[Italy]]\n| branch        = *[[Royal Sardinian Navy]]\n* Italian Royal Navy (''[[Regia Marina]]'')\n| serviceyears  = 1852\u20131903\n| serviceyears_label =\n| rank          = [[Vice Admiral]]\n| rank_label    =\n| servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records -->\n| unit          =\n| commands      = * {{ship|Italian cruiser|Colombo||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}}\n* Arsenal of [[Taranto]]\n* 2nd Naval Division, Permanent Squadron\n* Naval Squadron\n* 1st Division, 1st Squadron\n* [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897-1898)|International Squadron]]\n* 3rd Maritime District\n* Supreme Council of the Navy\n| battles_label =\n| battles       = * [[Second Italian War of Independence]]\n* [[Third Italian War of Independence]]\n* [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]]\n* [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897-1898)|Intervention in Crete]]\n| awards        =\n| memorials     =\n| parents       =\n| father        =\n| mother        =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced -->\n| children      =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n| signature     =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        =\n}}{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Grace (style)|His Grace]]\n| name          = Duke of [[Castelvari]] and [[Zoagli]]\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| imagesize     =\n| order         =\n| term_start    =\n| term_end      =\n| monarch       =\n| predecessor   =\n| successor     = Giuseppe Canevaro\n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| blank1 = Title\n| data1 = Duke of [[Castelvari]] and [[Zoagli]]\n| blank2 = Tenure\n| data2 = {{nowrap| ?&nbsp;\u201330 December 1926}}\n| blank3 = Other titles\n| data3 = Count of [[Santander, Spain|Santander]]\n| nationality   = Italian\n| party         =\n| parents       = Giuseppe and Francesca Velaga\n| education     =\n| alma_mater    =\n| spouse        = Ersilia Cozzi\n| children      = Giuseppe Canevaro\n}}\n\n====Battle of Lissa====\n\nOn 20 July 1866, ''Re di Portogallo'' played a particularly prominent role in the [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]] against the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] fleet.<ref name=treccani/> She first opened fire on the Austrian steam [[corvette]] {{SMS|Erzherzog Friedrich|1857|6}}, scoring a hit below the [[waterline]] that opened a leak that caused more water to enter  ''Erzherzog Friedrich'' than her pumps could handle, forcing '' Erzherzog Friedrich'' to retreat in the direction of Lissa. While chasing the damaged ''Erzherzog Friedrich'', ''Re di Portogallo'' sighted the Austrian steam [[ship-of-the-line]] {{SMS|Kaiser|1858|6}}, which, although seriously damaged by a broadside fired by the Italian [[Ironclad warship|ironclad]] [[Naval ram|ram]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Affondatore||2}}, was approaching to defend ''Erzherzog Friedrich''.<ref name=Martino>Ermanno Martino, ''Lissa 1866: perch\u00e9?'' in ''Storia Militare'' n. 214 and 215, July\u2013August 2011 (Italian).</ref><ref name=benninghof>{{cite web |url=http://www.avalanchepress.com/Battle_of_Lissa.php |last=Benninghof |first=Mike |title=Deadly Fishermen: The Battle of Lissa, 20 July 1866 |website=Avalanche Press |date=September 2007}}</ref> ''Re di Portogallo'' attempted to ram ''Kaiser'', but ''Kaiser'' steered toward ''Re di Portogallo'' and the two ships collided violently head-on.<ref name=Martino/> ''Kaiser'' had the worst of the collision, which badly damaged her [[Bow (ship)|bow]], destroyed her [[bowsprit]], and left her [[Figurehead (object)|figurehead]], a wooden statue of the Austrian emperor Kaiser [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]], stuck in the [[Hull (ship)|hull]] of ''Re di Portogallo''; it became an Italian war trophy.<ref name=Martino/><ref name=benninghof/> Entangled with ''Kaiser'', ''Re di Portogallo'' pummeled her with gunfire at close range, inflicting many casualties on her crew and bringing down her [[foresail]], which crashed onto her [[Funnel (ship)|funnel]]. ''Re di Portogallo'' put her engines astern to pull away from ''Kaiser'' and maneuver to ram her again, but could not resume her attack because smoke had concealed ''Kaiser'', which the officers of ''Re di Portogallo'' mistakenly believed may have sunk. As the battle continued ''Re di Portogallo'' found herself surrounded by four Austrian ships, but she managed to escape from them thanks to the ability of her commander, Riboty.<ref name=Martino/> One of the Italian ships most heavily involved in the battle,<ref name=treccani/> ''Re di Portogallo'' suffered serious damage, including the loss of her [[anchor]]s and some of her boats and having {{convert|18|m|ft}} of her armor dislodged, most of this damage occurring during the duel with ''Kaiser''. Although the outcome of the Battle of Lissa ultimately was disastrous for the Italian fleet,<ref name=Martino/> Canevaro received a second award of the Silver Medal for Military Valor,<ref name=treccani/> while ''Re di Portogallo''{{'}}s commanding officer Riboty received the [[Gold Medal of Military Valor]].<ref>[http://www.marina.difesa.it/storiacultura/storia/medaglie/Pagine/RibotyAugusto.aspx marina.difesa.it Augusto Riboty]</ref>\n\n====1870s\u20131890s====\n\nPromoted to ''[[Frigate captain|capitano di fregata]]'' in 1869, Canevaro served as a [[naval attach\u00e9]] at the Italian embassy in [[London]] from March 1874 to August 1876. From January 1877 to March 1879, while in command of the [[cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Colombo||2}}, he circumnavigated the globe, departing Italy, transiting the [[Suez Canal]], skirting [[Asia]], visiting ports in [[China]] and the [[Netherlands East Indies]] \u2013 where ''Colombo'' recovered the body of the Italian general and politician [[Nino Bixio]], who had died of [[cholera]] in [[Banda Aceh]] on [[Sumatra]] in 1873 \u2013 and then went on to [[Empire of Japan|Japan]], [[Russia]] (including [[Siberia]]), [[Australia]] and the [[Americas]]. After transiting the [[Strait of Magellan]] into the Atlantic Ocean, ''Colombo'' steamed up the coast of [[South America]] to the [[Caribbean]], then crossed the Atlantic to return to Italy.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nPromoted to ''[[Ship-of-the-line captain|capitano di vascello]]'', Canevaro performed various important duties, including service as chief-of-staff of the 3rd Maritime Department headquartered at [[Venice]], second-in-command of the [[Italian Naval Academy]], and commanding officer of the ironclad [[battleship]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}}. In 1884, while in command of ''Italia'', he played an active role in humanitarian work and [[public health]] during a cholera epidemic in [[La Spezia]], and he received the [[Silver Medal for Civil Valor]] for these efforts.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nPromoted to [[counter admiral]] (the equivalent of [[rear admiral]]) in 1887,<ref name=treccani/> Canevaro assumed command of the [[arsenal]] of [[Taranto]] and later of the 2nd Naval Division of the Permanent Squadron.<ref name=treccani/> He was promoted to [[vice admiral]] in 1893,<ref name=treccani/> and [[King of Italy|King]] [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]] appointed him a [[Senator of the Kingdom of Italy]] \u2013 an appointment for life \u2013 in 1896,<ref name=treccani/> the same year in which he assumed command of the ''Regia Marina''{{'}}s Naval Squadron.\n\n====International Squadron====\n\nIn February 1897, when a Christian uprising against the authority of the [[Ottoman Empire]] broke out on the island of [[Crete]], Canevaro arrived at Crete in command of the 1st Division of the 1st Squadron, consisting of the ironclad battleships {{ship|Italian ironclad|Sicilia||2}} (his flagship) and {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re Umberto||2}}, the [[protected cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Vesuvio||2}}, and the [[torpedo cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Euridice||2}}. Canevaro \u2013 who relieved the commander of the Italian naval squadron, Rear Admiral Gualterio, who had previously been in command of the 2nd Naval Division \u2013 assumed command of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] of warships off Crete on 16 or 17 February 1897 (sources differ) as the most senior admiral present, and took up duties as president of the \"Admirals Council,\" which consisted of the senior admirals present off Crete of each of the six countries participating in the International Squadron.<ref name=treccani/><ref name=nyt180297>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1897/02/18/102485379.pdf |title=The Powers Take Action; Sharp Warning Issued to Prince George Against Hostilities |work=The New York Times |date=18 February 1897}}</ref> The squadron put landing detachments ashore, but Christian insurgents continued to attack Ottoman forces and Canevaro soon ordered International Squadron ships to bombard them during February and March 1897 to stop the fighting. Although some political opponents in the Italian legislature attacked him for ordering the International Squadron to bombard the insurgents, Canevaro received great credit during his time in command of the squadron for his ability to exercise diplomacy and mediate disputes between the six Great Powers \u2013 [[Austria-Hungary]], [[France]], the [[German Empire]], Italy, the [[Russian Empire]], and the [[United Kingdom]] \u2013 making up the squadron and for the way in which he dealt with the confusing and anarchic situation on Crete, balancing humanitarian compassion and a spirit of conciliation in his dealings with Greek, Christian insurgent, and Ottoman forces on the island with the occasional need to use force to halt fighting and quell disturbances. Before leaving the International Squadron in 1898, Canevaro negotiated an agreement under which all combat on Crete would cease and [[Greece]] and the Ottoman Empire would withdraw their forces from the island in anticipation of the creation of an autonomous [[Cretan State]] under the [[suzerainty]] of the [[List of sultans of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman sultan]].<ref name=treccani/> Such was his reputation that when the creation of an office of [[High commissioner|High Commissioner]] of the Cretan State was proposed in the spring of 1898, Canevaro received an invitation to become the first high commissioner, but he declined the offer, and instead [[Prince George of Greece and Denmark]] became the first high commissioner when the Cretan State finally came into existence in December 1898.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n===Government minister===\n\nWhen [[Prime Minister of Italy]] [[Antonio Starabba, Marchese di Rudin\u00ec]], formed the government for his fifth ministry, Canevaro turned over command of the International Squadron to its next-most-senior admiral, Rear Admiral [[\u00c9douard Pottier]] of the [[French Navy]], and returned to Italy to serve as di Rudini\u2032s [[Italian Minister of the Navy|Minister of the Navy]]. Taking office on 1 June 1898, he served only four weeks, until the di Rudini government was replaced on 29 June 1898 by that of Prime Minister [[General officer|General]] [[Luigi Pelloux]]. On the same day Pelloux took office, Canevaro changed portfolios to become the [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs]].<ref name=treccani/> In his new role, he attempted to continue Italy\u2032s policy of loyalty to the [[Triple Alliance (1882)|Triple Alliance]] with Austria-Hungary and the German Empire and of continued warm relations with the United Kingdom, but at the same time worked toward relaxing tensions with France, and he conducted secret negotiations with the French for a commercial treaty, which the countries signed on 26 November 1898. He also resisted pressure from Germany to change the status of the Cretan State, supporting its continuation as an autonomous state under the suzerainty of the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nHowever, despite his successes in negotiations on Crete while in command of the International Squadron, Canevaro's talent for leading military forces did not translate into success in international diplomacy when it came to larger issues. During the [[Fashoda Crisis]] of 1899 between France and the United Kingdom, Canevaro conducted intensive diplomacy as part of the ongoing European \"[[Scramble for Africa]]\" in an effort to gain French and British recognition of an Italian interest in [[Libya]], but when the French and British concluded an agreement on 21 March 1899 that resolved the crisis, they offered no such recognition. Canevaro also was unsuccessful when in the wake of a number of anarchist attacks in [[Europe]] \u2013 one of which resulted in the stabbing death of [[Empress of Austria]] and [[Queen of Hungary]] [[Empress Elisabeth of Austria|Elizabeth]] on 10 September 1898 \u2013 he proposed an international anti-anarchist conference of diplomats and government security and judicial officials to address the situation; although some countries agreed to participate, the conference never took place.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nA final blow to Canevaro's diplomatic career came in the \"San Mun Affair\" of 1899, in which Italy demanded that the [[Chinese Empire]] grant it a lease for a naval coaling station at [[China]]'s [[Sanmen Bay]] (known as \"San-Mun Bay\" to the Italians) similar to the lease the German Empire had secured in 1898 at [[Kiautschou Bay concession|Kiaochow Bay]]. From Sanmen Bay, Italy hoped to establish an area of influence in [[Chekiang]]. The Russian Empire and the [[United States]] opposed the Italian demand, but the Italian ambassador in China, [[Renato De Martino]], led Canevaro to believe that the area was ripe for the taking. The British government, although ambivalent toward the Italian move, gave its approval as long as Italy did not use force against the Chinese, but the British did not inform Canevaro that the United Kingdom\u2032s representatives in China had advised that Italy could not achieve its goals without using force. Believing the opportunity to pursue Italy's interests in China was at hand, Canevaro had de Martino pass Italy\u2032s demands to the Chinese imperial government in the winter of 1899, but the Chinese summarily rejected them on 4 March 1899. On 8 March, Canevaro instructed De Martino to present the demands again as an ultimatum and authorized the [[armored cruiser]] ''[[Italian cruiser Marco Polo|Marco Polo]]'' and [[protected cruiser]] ''[[Italian cruiser Elba|Elba]]'' to occupy the bay. When the British ambassador in [[Rome]] reminded him that the United Kingdom did not support an Italian use of force, Canevaro issued a counterorder cancelling his authorization to use the two [[cruiser]]s in the bay, but De Martino received the counterorder before he received the original authorization to employ the ships. Unable to decipher the counterorder, De Martino presented the Italian ultimatum to China again on 10 March 1899, and China immediately refused to comply. Italy withdrew its ultimatum, becoming at the end of the 19th century the first and only [[Western world|Western]] power to fail to achieve its territorial goals in China. The fiasco was an embarrassment that gave Italy \u2013 still stung by its defeat at the hands of the [[Ethiopian Empire]] in the [[Battle of Adwa|Battle of Adowa]] in 1896 \u2013 the appearance of a third-rate power. On 14 March 1899, Canevaro attempted to present the affair to the [[Parliament of the Kingdom of Italy|Italian Parliament]] in a positive light, saying that be believed that China had rejected the Italian ultimatum in order to maintain a positive and productive relationship with Italy uninterrupted by negotiations over the bay, but such was the domestic criticism of the Italian failure as a humiliation and international criticism of it as a needless and unjustified provocation that Pelloux announced the resignation of his entire cabinet on 14 May 1899. He excluded Canevaro from the new cabinet he established that day.<ref name=treccani/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DUUCp8YQc5kC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=felice+napoleone+canevaro&source=bl&ots=00aY0ghOzd&sig=zzNPUpZ6p3LihTwtNRWGAHd-FX0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ2fygxLLYAhUE2mMKHaCSA9I4ChDoAQg3MAM#v=onepage&q=de%20martino&f=false |last=Smith |first=Shirley Ann |title=Imperial Designs: Italians in China, 1900\u20131947 |location=Madison, New Jersey |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-61147-502-9 |pages=8\u201310}}</ref>\n\n===Later naval service===\n\nCanevaro returned to the navy, commanding the 3rd Maritime District from 16 July 1900 to 16 January 1902 and presiding over the [[Supreme Council of the Navy]] from 16 January 1902 until 6 July 1903. He then retired and was placed on the reserve list, although in retirement he was promoted to vice admiral of the navy on 1 December 1923. He died at [[Venice]] on 30 December 1926.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n===Italian awards and honors===\n\n[[File:Cavaliere di gran Croce Regno SSML BAR.svg|100px]] Knight of the Grand Cross decorated with the Great Cordon of the [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]\n\n[[File:Cavaliere di Gran Croce OCI Kingdom BAR.svg|100px]] Knight of the Grand Cross decorated with the Great Cordon of the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]]\n\n[[File:Commendatore OMS BAR.svg|100px]] [[Commander (order)|Commander]] of the [[Military Order of Savoy]]\n\n[[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|100px]] [[Silver Medal of Military Valour]] (two awards)\n\n[[File:Valor civile silver medal BAR.svg|100px]] [[Silver Medal for Civil Valor]]\n\n[[File:Mauriziana BAR.svg|100px]] [[Maurician medal]]\n\n[[File:CampagneGuerreIndipendenza.png|100px]] [[Commemorative Medal of the Unity of Italy|Commemorative Medal for the Campaigns of the War of Independence]] (with three bars)\n\n[[File:Medaglia a ricordo dell'Unit\u00e0 d'Italia BAR.svg|100px]] [[Commemorative Medal of the Unity of Italy]]\n\n===Foreign awards and honors===\n\n[[File:ESP Isabella Catholic Order COM.svg|100px]] [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]] ([[Restoration (Spain)|Kingdom of Spain]])\n\n[[File:PRT Ordem de Nossa Senhora da Conceicao de Vila Vicosa Cavaleiro ribbon.svg|100px]]  Commander of the [[Order of the Immaculate Conception of Vila Vi\u00e7osa]] ([[Kingdom of Portugal]])\n\n[[File:Medaille commemorative de la Campagne d'Italie 1859 ribbon.svg|100px]] [[Commemorative medal of the 1859 Italian Campaign]] ([[Second French Empire]])\n\n== In popular culture ==\nCanevaro (spelled \"Canavaro\") is mentioned in [[Nikos Kazantzakis]]'s novel ''[[Zorba the Greek]]'' and the subsequent [[Zorba the Greek (film)|film]] and [[Zorba (musical)|musical]] of the same name, as the admiral and former lover of key character Madame Hortense, who thereafter calls Zorba by his name.\n\nOne of the main streets of the city center in [[Chania]] on Crete, ''odos Kanevarou'', is named after Canevaro.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Italy|Politics|War}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |first=Paolo Alberini e Franco |last=Prosperini |title=Uomini della Marina \u2013 Dizionario bibliografico |location=Roma |publisher=SMMM |year=2015 |pages=117\u2013118 |isbn=978-88-98485-95-6 |language=Italian}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Felice Napoleone Canevaro}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raffaele Cappelli]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Kingdom of Italy|years=1898\u20131899}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emilio, marquis Visconti-Venosta]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canevaro, Felice Napoleone}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1926 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian military personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian military personnel]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian politicians]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Naval ministers]]\n[[Category:Italian admirals]]\n[[Category:People from Lima]]\n[[Category:Italian military people of the wars of Italian unification]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Italy]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Military Order of Savoy]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the Immaculate Conception of Vila Vi\u00e7osa]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Maurician medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Medal of Military Valor]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Crown (Italy)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   =\n | name               = Felice Napoleone Canevaro\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   =\n | image              = File:Felice Napoleone Canevaro.jpg\n | image_size         = 250px\n | image_upright      =\n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = Felice Napoleone Canevaro\n | caption            = Felice Napoleone Canevaro in 1898\n | order              =\n | office             = [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n | term_start         = 29 June 1898\n | term_end           = 14 May 1899\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            = [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n | president          =\n | governor_general   =\n | primeminister      = [[Luigi Pelloux]]\n | taoiseach          =\n | chancellor         =\n | governor           =\n | vicepresident      =\n | viceprimeminister  =\n | deputy             =\n | lieutenant         =\n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup =\n | constituency       =\n | majority           =\n | predecessor        = [[Raffaele Cappelli]]\n | successor          = [[Emilio Visconti Venosta]]\n | prior_term         =\n | order2             =\n | office2            =  [[Italian Minister of the Navy]]\n | term_start2        =  1 June 1898\n | term_end2          =  29 June 1898\n | alongside2         =\n | monarch2           =  [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n | president2         =\n | governor_general2  =\n | primeminister2     =  [[Antonio di Rudini]]\n | chancellor2        =\n | taoiseach2         =\n | governor2          =\n | vicepresident2     =\n | viceprimeminister2 =\n | deputy2            =\n | lieutenant2        =\n | succeeding2        =\n | predecessor2       =  [[Alessandro Assinari di San Marzano]]\n | successor2         =  Giuseppe Palumbo\n | parliamentarygroup2=\n | constituency2      =\n | majority2          =\n | prior_term2        =\n| order3             =\n | office3            =  [[Senator of the Kingdom of Italy]]\n | term_start3        =\n | term_end3          =\n | alongside3         =\n | monarch3           =  [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]]\n[[:it:XIX legislatura del Regno d'Italia|XIX Legislature]]\n | data3              =\n | legislature3       =\n | president3         =\n | governor_general3  =\n | primeminister3     =\n | chancellor3        =\n | taoiseach3         =\n | governor3          =\n | vicepresident3     =\n | viceprimeminister3 =\n | deputy3            =\n | lieutenant3        =\n | succeeding3        =\n | predecessor3       =\n | successor3         =\n | parliamentarygroup3=\n | constituency3      =\n | majority3          =\n | prior_term3        =\n}}\n\n'''Felice Napoleone Canevaro''' (7 July 1838 \u2013 30 December 1926) was an Italian admiral and politician and a [[Senate of the Kingdom of Italy|senator of the Kingdom of Italy]]. He served as both Minister of the Navy and [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] and was a recipient of the [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]. In his naval career, he was best known for his actions during the [[Italian Wars of Independence]] and later as commander of the [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] off [[Crete]] in 1897\u20131898.\n\n==Biography==\nThe descendant of a [[Liguria]]n family originally from [[Zoagli]], Canevaro was born in [[Lima]], [[Peru]], to Giuseppe and Francesca Velaga.<ref name=treccani>{{cite web |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/felice-napoleone-canevaro_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ |first=Gabriele  |last=Mariano |title=Canevaro, Felice Napoleone |work=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani  |volume=18 |year=1975 |language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n===Naval career===\nIn 1852, Canevaro was admitted to the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]]'s Royal Navy School at [[Genoa]], completing the course of instruction in 1855 and receiving a [[Commissioned officer|commission]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign second class]].\n\n====Italian Wars of Independence====\nIn 1859, with the rank of second [[Lieutenant (naval)|lieutenant]], Canevaro took part in [[Royal Sardinian Navy]] operations in the [[Adriatic Sea]] aboard the [[Troop transport|transport]] ''Beroldo'' and the sailing [[frigate]] {{ship|Italian frigate|Des Geneys||2}} during the [[Second Italian War of Independence]].<ref name=treccani/>\n\nIn 1860, Canevaro arrived in [[Palermo]], [[Sicily]], aboard {{ship|Italian frigate|Maria Adelaide||2}}, the [[flagship]] of the Sardinian [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]]. When the supporters of the Italian nationalist leader [[General officer|General]] [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] organized their navy, he resigned from the Royal Sardinian Navy to enlist in the Garibaldian navy. Aboard the [[steam frigate]] ''Tukory'' on the night of 13 August 1860, Canevaro distinguished himself during an unsuccessful attempt to board the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]] steam [[ship-of-the-line]] ''Monarca'' while she was anchored in the port of [[Castellammare di Stabia]]. He received the [[Silver Medal of Military Valor]] for his actions during this engagement.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nIn the autumn of 1860, Canevarro was reinstated in the Royal Sardinian Navy. While embarked on the Sardinian steam frigate {{ship|Italian frigate|Carlo Alberto|1853|2}} from December 1860 to March 1861, he took part in the [[Siege of Gaeta (1860)|Siege of Gaeta]] and a [[siege]] of [[Messina]] during operations in which ''Carlo Alberto'' repeatedly exchanged fire with hostile forces at close range along the coast. After the campaign, he was made a Knight of the [[Military Order of Savoy]], and in 1863, he was promoted to ''[[Lieutenant (naval)|luogotenente de vascello]]''. In 1865\u20131866, Canevaro was on board the steam frigate {{ship|Italian frigate|Principe Umberto||2}}, under the command [[Guglielmo Acton]], during a long cruise that included a [[transatlantic voyage]], operations along the [[Atlantic]] coast of [[South America]], a transit of the [[Strait of Magellan]] into the [[Pacific Ocean]], and steaming up the coast of [[Chile]].<ref name=treccani/>\n[[File:Italian battleship Italia officers and guns.jpg|300px|thumb|left|Canevaro and the [[Commissioned officer|officers]] of the [[battleship]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}} pose under a pair of her {{convert|17|in|mm|adj=on|0}} guns.]]\nOn returning to Italy, he was assigned to the [[broadside ironclad]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re di Portogallo||2}}, commanded by Augusto Riboty. Aboard ''Re di Portogallo'', he took part in 1866 in the [[Third Italian War of Independence]], during which the ship was engaged in operations against the fortress of [[Vis (island)|Lissa]] in the [[Adriatic Sea]]. As [[flagship]] of the 3rd Division, and with Canevaro aboard as the division's chief-of-staff, ''Re di Portogallo'' led the division's attack on [[Porto San Giorgio]] on 18 July 1866.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n[[File:The Admirals of the Powers in Cretan Waters.JPG|300px|left|thumb|\"The Admirals of the Powers in Cretan Waters\" (Sketch from ''[[Black and White (magazine)|Black and White]]'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1897). Canevaro, serving at the time as commander of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]], is fourth from left.]]\n[[File:Bombardment of Canea 21 February 1897.JPG|300px|thumb|left|Illustration as it appeared in ''[[The Graphic]]'' on 13 March 1897 of warships of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] bombarding Christian insurgents above [[Chania]], [[Crete]], on 21 February 1897. It probably is reversed.]]\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  =\n| name              = Felice Napoleono Canevaro\n| honorific_suffix  =\n| image         =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| native_name       =\n| native_name_lang  =\n| birth_name    =\n| other_name    =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1838|07|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lima]], [[Peru]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1926|12|30|1838|07|07|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Venice]], [[Italy]]\n| placeofburial_label =\n| placeofburial =\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = *[[Kingdom of Sardinia]]\n* [[Italy]]\n| branch        = *[[Royal Sardinian Navy]]\n* Italian Royal Navy (''[[Regia Marina]]'')\n| serviceyears  = 1852\u20131903\n| serviceyears_label =\n| rank          = [[Vice Admiral]]\n| rank_label    =\n| servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records -->\n| unit          =\n| commands      = * {{ship|Italian cruiser|Colombo||2}}\n* {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}}\n* Arsenal of [[Taranto]]\n* 2nd Naval Division, Permanent Squadron\n* Naval Squadron\n* 1st Division, 1st Squadron\n* [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897-1898)|International Squadron]]\n* 3rd Maritime District\n* Supreme Council of the Navy\n| battles_label =\n| battles       = * [[Second Italian War of Independence]]\n* [[Third Italian War of Independence]]\n* [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]]\n* [[International Squadron (Crete intervention, 1897-1898)|Intervention in Crete]]\n| awards        =\n| memorials     =\n| parents       =\n| father        =\n| mother        =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced -->\n| children      =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n| signature     =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        =\n}}{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Grace (style)|His Grace]]\n| name          = Duke of [[Castelvari]] and [[Zoagli]]\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| imagesize     =\n| order         =\n| term_start    =\n| term_end      =\n| monarch       =\n| predecessor   =\n| successor     = Giuseppe Canevaro\n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   =\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| blank1 = Title\n| data1 = Duke of [[Castelvari]] and [[Zoagli]]\n| blank2 = Tenure\n| data2 = {{nowrap| ?&nbsp;\u201330 December 1926}}\n| blank3 = Other titles\n| data3 = Count of [[Santander, Spain|Santander]]\n| nationality   = Italian\n| party         =\n| parents       = Giuseppe and Francesca Velaga\n| education     =\n| alma_mater    =\n| spouse        = Ersilia Cozzi\n| children      = Giuseppe Canevaro\n}}\n\n====Battle of Lissa====\n\nOn 20 July 1866, ''Re di Portogallo'' played a particularly prominent role in the [[Battle of Lissa (1866)|Battle of Lissa]] against the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] fleet.<ref name=treccani/> She first opened fire on the Austrian steam [[corvette]] {{SMS|Erzherzog Friedrich|1857|6}}, scoring a hit below the [[waterline]] that opened a leak that caused more water to enter  ''Erzherzog Friedrich'' than her pumps could handle, forcing '' Erzherzog Friedrich'' to retreat in the direction of Lissa. While chasing the damaged ''Erzherzog Friedrich'', ''Re di Portogallo'' sighted the Austrian steam [[ship-of-the-line]] {{SMS|Kaiser|1858|6}}, which, although seriously damaged by a broadside fired by the Italian [[Ironclad warship|ironclad]] [[Naval ram|ram]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Affondatore||2}}, was approaching to defend ''Erzherzog Friedrich''.<ref name=Martino>Ermanno Martino, ''Lissa 1866: perch\u00e9?'' in ''Storia Militare'' n. 214 and 215, July\u2013August 2011 (Italian).</ref><ref name=benninghof>{{cite web |url=http://www.avalanchepress.com/Battle_of_Lissa.php |last=Benninghof |first=Mike |title=Deadly Fishermen: The Battle of Lissa, 20 July 1866 |website=Avalanche Press |date=September 2007}}</ref> ''Re di Portogallo'' attempted to ram ''Kaiser'', but ''Kaiser'' steered toward ''Re di Portogallo'' and the two ships collided violently head-on.<ref name=Martino/> ''Kaiser'' had the worst of the collision, which badly damaged her [[Bow (ship)|bow]], destroyed her [[bowsprit]], and left her [[Figurehead (object)|figurehead]], a wooden statue of the Austrian emperor Kaiser [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]], stuck in the [[Hull (ship)|hull]] of ''Re di Portogallo''; it became an Italian war trophy.<ref name=Martino/><ref name=benninghof/> Entangled with ''Kaiser'', ''Re di Portogallo'' pummeled her with gunfire at close range, inflicting many casualties on her crew and bringing down her [[foresail]], which crashed onto her [[Funnel (ship)|funnel]]. ''Re di Portogallo'' put her engines astern to pull away from ''Kaiser'' and maneuver to ram her again, but could not resume her attack because smoke had concealed ''Kaiser'', which the officers of ''Re di Portogallo'' mistakenly believed may have sunk. As the battle continued ''Re di Portogallo'' found herself surrounded by four Austrian ships, but she managed to escape from them thanks to the ability of her commander, Riboty.<ref name=Martino/> One of the Italian ships most heavily involved in the battle,<ref name=treccani/> ''Re di Portogallo'' suffered serious damage, including the loss of her [[anchor]]s and some of her boats and having {{convert|18|m|ft}} of her armor dislodged, most of this damage occurring during the duel with ''Kaiser''. Although the outcome of the Battle of Lissa ultimately was disastrous for the Italian fleet,<ref name=Martino/> Canevaro received a second award of the Silver Medal for Military Valor,<ref name=treccani/> while ''Re di Portogallo''{{'}}s commanding officer Riboty received the [[Gold Medal of Military Valor]].<ref>[http://www.marina.difesa.it/storiacultura/storia/medaglie/Pagine/RibotyAugusto.aspx marina.difesa.it Augusto Riboty]</ref>\n\n====1870s\u20131890s====\n\nPromoted to ''[[Frigate captain|capitano di fregata]]'' in 1869, Canevaro served as a [[naval attach\u00e9]] at the Italian embassy in [[London]] from March 1874 to August 1876. From January 1877 to March 1879, while in command of the [[cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Colombo||2}}, he circumnavigated the globe, departing Italy, transiting the [[Suez Canal]], skirting [[Asia]], visiting ports in [[China]] and the [[Netherlands East Indies]] \u2013 where ''Colombo'' recovered the body of the Italian general and politician [[Nino Bixio]], who had died of [[cholera]] in [[Banda Aceh]] on [[Sumatra]] in 1873 \u2013 and then went on to [[Empire of Japan|Japan]], [[Russia]] (including [[Siberia]]), [[Australia]] and the [[Americas]]. After transiting the [[Strait of Magellan]] into the Atlantic Ocean, ''Colombo'' steamed up the coast of [[South America]] to the [[Caribbean]], then crossed the Atlantic to return to Italy.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nPromoted to ''[[Ship-of-the-line captain|capitano di vascello]]'', Canevaro performed various important duties, including service as chief-of-staff of the 3rd Maritime Department headquartered at [[Venice]], second-in-command of the [[Italian Naval Academy]], and commanding officer of the ironclad [[battleship]] {{ship|Italian ironclad|Italia||2}}. In 1884, while in command of ''Italia'', he played an active role in humanitarian work and [[public health]] during a cholera epidemic in [[La Spezia]], and he received the [[Silver Medal for Civil Valor]] for these efforts.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nPromoted to [[counter admiral]] (the equivalent of [[rear admiral]]) in 1887,<ref name=treccani/> Canevaro assumed command of the [[arsenal]] of [[Taranto]] and later of the 2nd Naval Division of the Permanent Squadron.<ref name=treccani/> He was promoted to [[vice admiral]] in 1893,<ref name=treccani/> and [[King of Italy|King]] [[Umberto I of Italy|Umberto I]] appointed him a [[Senator of the Kingdom of Italy]] \u2013 an appointment for life \u2013 in 1896,<ref name=treccani/> the same year in which he assumed command of the ''Regia Marina''{{'}}s Naval Squadron.\n\n====International Squadron====\n\nIn February 1897, when a Christian uprising against the authority of the [[Ottoman Empire]] broke out on the island of [[Crete]], Canevaro arrived at Crete in command of the 1st Division of the 1st Squadron, consisting of the ironclad battleships {{ship|Italian ironclad|Sicilia||2}} (his flagship) and {{ship|Italian ironclad|Re Umberto||2}}, the [[protected cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Vesuvio||2}}, and the [[torpedo cruiser]] {{ship|Italian cruiser|Euridice||2}}. Canevaro \u2013 who relieved the commander of the Italian naval squadron, Rear Admiral Gualterio, who had previously been in command of the 2nd Naval Division \u2013 assumed command of the [[International Squadron (Cretan intervention, 1897\u20131898)|International Squadron]] of warships off Crete on 16 or 17 February 1897 (sources differ) as the most senior admiral present, and took up duties as president of the \"Admirals Council,\" which consisted of the senior admirals present off Crete of each of the six countries participating in the International Squadron.<ref name=treccani/><ref name=nyt180297>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1897/02/18/102485379.pdf |title=The Powers Take Action; Sharp Warning Issued to Prince George Against Hostilities |work=The New York Times |date=18 February 1897}}</ref> The squadron put landing detachments ashore, but Christian insurgents continued to attack Ottoman forces and Canevaro soon ordered International Squadron ships to bombard them during February and March 1897 to stop the fighting. Although some political opponents in the Italian legislature attacked him for ordering the International Squadron to bombard the insurgents, Canevaro received great credit during his time in command of the squadron for his ability to exercise diplomacy and mediate disputes between the six Great Powers \u2013 [[Austria-Hungary]], [[France]], the [[German Empire]], Italy, the [[Russian Empire]], and the [[United Kingdom]] \u2013 making up the squadron and for the way in which he dealt with the confusing and anarchic situation on Crete, balancing humanitarian compassion and a spirit of conciliation in his dealings with Greek, Christian insurgent, and Ottoman forces on the island with the occasional need to use force to halt fighting and quell disturbances. Before leaving the International Squadron in 1898, Canevaro negotiated an agreement under which all combat on Crete would cease and [[Greece]] and the Ottoman Empire would withdraw their forces from the island in anticipation of the creation of an autonomous [[Cretan State]] under the [[suzerainty]] of the [[List of sultans of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman sultan]].<ref name=treccani/> Such was his reputation that when the creation of an office of [[High commissioner|High Commissioner]] of the Cretan State was proposed in the spring of 1898, Canevaro received an invitation to become the first high commissioner, but he declined the offer, and instead [[Prince George of Greece and Denmark]] became the first high commissioner when the Cretan State finally came into existence in December 1898.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n===Government minister===\n\nWhen [[Prime Minister of Italy]] [[Antonio Starabba, Marchese di Rudin\u00ec]], formed the government for his fifth ministry, Canevaro turned over command of the International Squadron to its next-most-senior admiral, Rear Admiral [[\u00c9douard Pottier]] of the [[French Navy]], and returned to Italy to serve as di Rudini\u2032s [[Italian Minister of the Navy|Minister of the Navy]]. Taking office on 1 June 1898, he served only four weeks, until the di Rudini government was replaced on 29 June 1898 by that of Prime Minister [[General officer|General]] [[Luigi Pelloux]]. On the same day Pelloux took office, Canevaro changed portfolios to become the [[Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs]].<ref name=treccani/> In his new role, he attempted to continue Italy\u2032s policy of loyalty to the [[Triple Alliance (1882)|Triple Alliance]] with Austria-Hungary and the German Empire and of continued warm relations with the United Kingdom, but at the same time worked toward relaxing tensions with France, and he conducted secret negotiations with the French for a commercial treaty, which the countries signed on 26 November 1898. He also resisted pressure from Germany to change the status of the Cretan State, supporting its continuation as an autonomous state under the suzerainty of the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nHowever, despite his successes in negotiations on Crete while in command of the International Squadron, Canevaro's talent for leading military forces did not translate into success in international diplomacy when it came to larger issues. During the [[Fashoda Crisis]] of 1899 between France and the United Kingdom, Canevaro conducted intensive diplomacy as part of the ongoing European \"[[Scramble for Africa]]\" in an effort to gain French and British recognition of an Italian interest in [[Libya]], but when the French and British concluded an agreement on 21 March 1899 that resolved the crisis, they offered no such recognition. Canevaro also was unsuccessful when in the wake of a number of anarchist attacks in [[Europe]] \u2013 one of which resulted in the stabbing death of [[Empress of Austria]] and [[Queen of Hungary]] [[Empress Elisabeth of Austria|Elizabeth]] on 10 September 1898 \u2013 he proposed an international anti-anarchist conference of diplomats and government security and judicial officials to address the situation; although some countries agreed to participate, the conference never took place.<ref name=treccani/>\n\nA final blow to Canevaro's diplomatic career came in the \"San Mun Affair\" of 1899, in which Italy demanded that the [[Chinese Empire]] grant it a lease for a naval coaling station at [[China]]'s [[Sanmen Bay]] (known as \"San-Mun Bay\" to the Italians) similar to the lease the German Empire had secured in 1898 at [[Kiautschou Bay concession|Kiaochow Bay]]. From Sanmen Bay, Italy hoped to establish an area of influence in [[Chekiang]]. The Russian Empire and the [[United States]] opposed the Italian demand, but the Italian ambassador in China, [[Renato De Martino]], led Canevaro to believe that the area was ripe for the taking. The British government, although ambivalent toward the Italian move, gave its approval as long as Italy did not use force against the Chinese, but the British did not inform Canevaro that the United Kingdom\u2032s representatives in China had advised that Italy could not achieve its goals without using force. Believing the opportunity to pursue Italy's interests in China was at hand, Canevaro had de Martino pass Italy\u2032s demands to the Chinese imperial government in the winter of 1899, but the Chinese summarily rejected them on 4 March 1899. On 8 March, Canevaro instructed De Martino to present the demands again as an ultimatum and authorized the [[armored cruiser]] ''[[Italian cruiser Marco Polo|Marco Polo]]'' and [[protected cruiser]] ''[[Italian cruiser Elba|Elba]]'' to occupy the bay. When the British ambassador in [[Rome]] reminded him that the United Kingdom did not support an Italian use of force, Canevaro issued a counterorder cancelling his authorization to use the two [[cruiser]]s in the bay, but De Martino received the counterorder before he received the original authorization to employ the ships. Unable to decipher the counterorder, De Martino presented the Italian ultimatum to China again on 10 March 1899, and China immediately refused to comply. Italy withdrew its ultimatum, becoming at the end of the 19th century the first and only [[Western world|Western]] power to fail to achieve its territorial goals in China. The fiasco was an embarrassment that gave Italy \u2013 still stung by its defeat at the hands of the [[Ethiopian Empire]] in the [[Battle of Adwa|Battle of Adowa]] in 1896 \u2013 the appearance of a third-rate power. On 14 March 1899, Canevaro attempted to present the affair to the [[Parliament of the Kingdom of Italy|Italian Parliament]] in a positive light, saying that be believed that China had rejected the Italian ultimatum in order to maintain a positive and productive relationship with Italy uninterrupted by negotiations over the bay, but such was the domestic criticism of the Italian failure as a humiliation and international criticism of it as a needless and unjustified provocation that Pelloux announced the resignation of his entire cabinet on 14 May 1899. He excluded Canevaro from the new cabinet he established that day.<ref name=treccani/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DUUCp8YQc5kC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=felice+napoleone+canevaro&source=bl&ots=00aY0ghOzd&sig=zzNPUpZ6p3LihTwtNRWGAHd-FX0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ2fygxLLYAhUE2mMKHaCSA9I4ChDoAQg3MAM#v=onepage&q=de%20martino&f=false |last=Smith |first=Shirley Ann |title=Imperial Designs: Italians in China, 1900\u20131947 |location=Madison, New Jersey |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-61147-502-9 |pages=8\u201310}}</ref>\n\n===Later naval service===\n\nCanevaro returned to the navy, commanding the 3rd Maritime District from 16 July 1900 to 16 January 1902 and presiding over the [[Supreme Council of the Navy]] from 16 January 1902 until 6 July 1903. He then retired and was placed on the reserve list, although in retirement he was promoted to vice admiral of the navy on 1 December 1923. He died at [[Venice]] on 30 December 1926.<ref name=treccani/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n===Italian awards and honors===\n\n[[File:Cavaliere di gran Croce Regno SSML BAR.svg|100px]] Knight of the Grand Cross decorated with the Great Cordon of the [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]\n\n[[File:Cavaliere di Gran Croce OCI Kingdom BAR.svg|100px]] Knight of the Grand Cross decorated with the Great Cordon of the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]]\n\n[[File:Commendatore OMS BAR.svg|100px]] [[Commander (order)|Commander]] of the [[Military Order of Savoy]]\n\n[[File:Valor militare silver medal BAR.svg|100px]] [[Silver Medal of Military Valour]] (two awards)\n\n[[File:Valor civile silver medal BAR.svg|100px]] [[Silver Medal for Civil Valor]]\n\n[[File:Mauriziana BAR.svg|100px]] [[Maurician medal]]\n\n[[File:CampagneGuerreIndipendenza.png|100px]] [[Commemorative Medal of the Unity of Italy|Commemorative Medal for the Campaigns of the War of Independence]] (with three bars)\n\n[[File:Medaglia a ricordo dell'Unit\u00e0 d'Italia BAR.svg|100px]] [[Commemorative Medal of the Unity of Italy]]\n\n===Foreign awards and honors===\n\n[[File:ESP Isabella Catholic Order COM.svg|100px]] [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]] ([[Restoration (Spain)|Kingdom of Spain]])\n\n[[File:PRT Ordem de Nossa Senhora da Conceicao de Vila Vicosa Cavaleiro ribbon.svg|100px]]  Commander of the [[Order of the Immaculate Conception of Vila Vi\u00e7osa]] ([[Kingdom of Portugal]])\n\n[[File:Medaille commemorative de la Campagne d'Italie 1859 ribbon.svg|100px]] [[Commemorative medal of the 1859 Italian Campaign]] ([[Second French Empire]])\n\n== In popular culture ==\nCanevaro (spelled \"Canavaro\") is mentioned in [[Nikos Kazantzakis]]'s novel ''[[Zorba the Greek]]'' and the subsequent [[Zorba the Greek (film)|film]] and [[Zorba (musical)|musical]] of the same name, as the admiral and former lover of key character Madame Hortense, who thereafter calls Zorbas by his name.\n\nOne of the main streets of the city center in [[Chania]] on Crete, ''odos Kanevarou'', is named after Canevaro.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Italy|Politics|War}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |first=Paolo Alberini e Franco |last=Prosperini |title=Uomini della Marina \u2013 Dizionario bibliografico |location=Roma |publisher=SMMM |year=2015 |pages=117\u2013118 |isbn=978-88-98485-95-6 |language=Italian}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Felice Napoleone Canevaro}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raffaele Cappelli]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Kingdom of Italy|years=1898\u20131899}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emilio, marquis Visconti-Venosta]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSOR